                1975            
Charles Revson of the Revlon Empire Dies

By ENID NEMYAUG. 25, 1975



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story















View page in TimesMachine





 August 25, 1975, Page 30 The New York Times Archives


Charles Haskell Revson, president of Revlon, Inc., the cosmetics giant, died yesterday of cancer at the Columbia‐Presbyterian Medical Center. He was 68 years old and lived in New Rochelle, N.Y.Mr. Revson, who built an empire from colorful nail enamel that a chemist friend heated over a Bunsen burner, was a man of unrelenting drive, unremitting standards, farranging imagination and an uncanny ability to spot a trend while it was still a distant breeze.A man who had been so excited with his first order for $400 that he wired his brother the news, and who had kept his business, alive in its first year by paying interest of 2 per cent a month to loan sharks, he presided at the time of his death over the largest cosmetics and fragrance company in the retail market. (It is exceeded in size in its field only by the Avon Corporation, which uses the door‐to‐door method of sales distribution.)Mr. Revson, son of a cigar packer who had emigrated from Russia, was born in Boston, on Oct. 11, 1906, and was brought up in Manchester, N. H. He came to New York at the age of 17. Through the influence of a cousin, he got a job selling $16.75 dresses on Seventh Avenue, but was happier when he was put in charge of the company's piece‐goods department.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

He entered the beauty business while still in his early 20's, selling the nail polish that was then, available—a thin, translucent coating in a few basic colos. He left his employer, the Elka Company, in 1932, when he was refused the job of national distributor. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Revlon was born the same year, when Mr. Revson and his older brother, Joseph, met Charles Lachman (the L in Revlon), a chemist who had experimented over a Bunsen burner and produced a formula for a creamy, opaque, nonstreak nail polish. The three pooled their resources, a matter of $300, and went into business in a room on Manhattan's West Side.Concentrated on SalonsThe company grew, even during the Depression, because of Mr. Revson's decision to concentrate his sales efforts on beauty salons, which were then in the midst of the permanentwave boom. Even after Revlon began to sell through department and drug stores, in 1937, the salon business remained its major preoccupation for some years. By 1941 Revlon had a near monopoly in the estimated total of 100,000 beauty salons throughout the country, selling in bulk to the professional operators, and to the women who bought their cosmetics at the salons. The dominance built up during that period exists to this day.Mr. Revson was generally recognized as the moving force of the company and the visionary bOth in new‐product development (in his younger days, he often walked‐around with nails dabbed with polish and hands striped with lipstick) and in the advertising that pushed Revlon to national prominence.Revlon introduced the concept of “matching lips and fingertips” in 1939—earlier, colors of lipstick and nail polish had not been thus coordinated, and there were only a few shades (generally light, medium and dark) in each. This was followed by magazine advertising that promoted Revlon's varied, glamorous colors and romantic names; it was consistently brilliant and considered the best in the industry. In 1951, the “Fire and Ice” advertisement was introduced; it is still considered one of the classics of the beauty businessDespite the extraordinary magazine impact, most of it sparked by Mr. Revson's demand for nothing less than perfection, Revlon's television efforts were, until 1955, mediocre, In that year, Revlon began sponsorship of “The $64,000 Question,” with a clause, unusual at the time, that gave it the right to abandon the program after 13 weeks should it prove a dud. After its first showing, Mr. Revson was unconvinced about its drawing power:“It's a turkey,” he told colleagues who gathered after the show.Swamped With DemandNevertheless, from the day the program went on the air, the company was swamped with dealer demand. Sales rose 54 per cent, earnings went up almost 200 per cent, and even the resultant quiz‐show scandals could not diminish the impact. Revlon shares, whiCh had just been offered to the public at $12 a, share, rose to $30 in three months.In the ensuing years, new products and use of advertising continued their parallel courses in pushing Revlon to the top of the industry. Cosmetics, skin care products, shampoos and hair sprays, fragrances and men's products, in a wide range, prices, spewed forth from the fertile minds of company and advertising executives, from Revlon's product‐development laboratory and from acquisition's. The trade names marketed by Revlon included Ultima II, Princess Marcella Borghese, Moon Drops, Intimate, Fianima, Replique, Miss Balmain, Etherea, Bill Blass, Braggi and Royal Pub. The advertising budget, $7.5‐million in 1955, grew to $52‐million by 1973.By the early nineteen‐sixties, Joseph Revson and Mr. Lachman had resigned from the company. A younger brother, Martin, who entered the business in 1935, resigned in 1958 and sued his brother on charges of fraud, misrepresentation and breach of agreement in a stock deal. The suit was settled out of court, but the brothers remained estranged until after Joseph's death in 1971. Martin Revson is now head of Dell Laboratories, manufacturer of inexpensive cosmetics.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Decision to DiversifyOne of Charles Revson's most orilliant business moves was his decision in 1966 to diversify his cosmetics empire by nibbling off a tiny piece of the hugely profitable pharmaceutical industry. Against the advice of most of his associates, he paid $67.5‐million for the United States Vitamin and Pharmaceutical Corporation, a sleepy drug company with modest sales of $21‐million a year.As he had with Revlon, Mr. Revson soon began adding products to the U.S.V. line. Cross‐licensing agreements with foreign companies brought with them the right to market new drugs in this country and elsewhere, and a 1971 exchange lagreement with the Ciba‐Geigy Corporbtion gave U.S.V. certain marketing rights, patents and trademarks for four widely used drugs, and marketing rights to 13 additional drugs. Revlon expanded into 11 new and different therapeutic categories and, in return, Ciba‐Geigy received $25‐million in cash and the rights to market an oral diabetic drug.Less than a decade after he had entered the pharmaceutical industry, 23 per cent of the sales of Revlon, Inc. and 28 per cent of its profits derived from sales of health products in the United States and 46 other countries.By 1974 the Revlon product range had grown to more than 3,500 individual items, sold in 85 countries. The company's sales totaled $605‐million and net earnings were $49.8‐million.Mr. Revson's business judgment was not, however, infallible. Involvements with businesses as diverse as plastic flowers and loungewear, made in Hong Kong, and sportswear, made in the United States, were terminated in a comparatively short time. The company's fouryear ownership of Evan‐Picone, the sportswear house, resulted in a loss of $1.75‐million when it was sold in 1966.Interest in ClothesAlthough his professional ventures into the fashion industry were peripheral and shortlived; Mr. Revson's personal interest in the clothes worn by his third wife, the former Lyn Fisher Sheresky (their 10‐year marriage ended in divorce in 1974), resulted in one of his most astute business tie‐ups.At one time, the late designer Norman Norell would send his collection to the Revlon office, where Mr. Revson selected styles for his wife. Liter, Mr. Revson began to accompany his wife to fashionable showroom openings.He thought so highly of the designer's talents that he made a business arrangement with him under which the Norell name went on Revlon's most prestigious perfume. It was fortuitous timing; the venture came just as a fragrance boom was beginning, and the new scent, Norell, became what many considered the first great American perfume. Mr. Revson, aware of the fragrance trend, soon followed Norell with Charlie; a less expensive scent aimed at a younger market.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Although Revlon was built on its sales to women, Mr. Revson employed few of them in key positions.“I don't think he trusted women's thinking to any degree,” commented one who knew him well, and who remembered his comment that “a man gets his strength from a woman and then he goes on from there.”Opposite Ends of RoomHowever, because of the nature of the cosmetics business, women were the objects of his principal business vendettas. He was loath to mention the name of his competitors, and it was known as the height of folly to invite the Revlon founder and Estee Lauder, a chief rival in the field, to the same party. When the two did find themselves in the same room, they pretended they weren't, and proceeded, with entourages, to opposite ends.Mr. Revson had the last word in earlier business feuds, although he did not retaliate publicly while they were going on. The late Elizabeth Arden called him “that man,” and he so named one of his men's fragrances. The late Helena Rubinstein referred to him as “the nail man.” After her death, he bought her Park Avenue triplex. He also made certain that he surmounted other cosmetics companies in the General Motors Building, home of Revlon's corporate headquarters. Estée Lauder's offices are on the 37th floor and Helena Rubinstein's, until a recent move, were the 32d; Revlon is at the top.The prestige built up by Estée Lauder, and the fact that Mr. Revson and Mrs. Lauder both moved with international society, perhaps accounted for Mr. Revson's increasing preoccupation with building up his own name in his later years.“Charles Revson” began to be used in advertising copy, and news releases went out on paper emblazoned with inch‐high gold letters outlining the name. And although he was known as Charles to his friends, he was not averse to the marketing of the name Charlie.Kept Eye on DetailsDespite his interest in the social whirl, and the amount of time he spent aboard the Ultima H, the 257‐foot, 1,200‐ton yacht he bought from Daniel K. Ludwig, multimillionaire shipbuilder, Mr. Revson never lost contact with his office. He was aware of the smallest details within the organization and was never hesitant in voicing opinion or criticism.“He chewed up executives the way some people chew vitamins,” said one chewed‐up executive, who noted that even the hefty financial rewards offered by the company were nut sufficient to prevent a considerable turnover in upper‐echelon personnel and in advertising agencies. At one time, the corporate headquarters was dubbed “one big revolving door.”At meetings, Mr. Revson had a reputation for lowering the heavy lids over his sharp blue eyes and assuming a sleepy look. The knowledgeable were aware that the pose did not affect his vision. He pounced when it was least expected, and conferences would go on long after everyone else was weary.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

His employes were rarely told that they did a good job, an omission many found frustrating. Others were irked at the atmosphere engendered by his personal likes and dislikes. Office romances were frowned on, women in pants were merely tolerated, and beards and brown shoes on male employes were restricted “not by dictum but by tone.”Enjoyed His SuccessMr. Revson fully enjoyed the accouterments of success—the yacht, the triplex, a country estate in Westchester, a chauffeur‐driven Rolls‐Royce, and the tailors and barbers who came to him. He enjoyed, too, helping friends in distress.As a man who never went to college, he took a particular satisfaction in seeing his name on medical centers and fellowships (the Charles Revson Diagnostic Center at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine, the Charles Revson Institute of Ophthalmology at. New York Medical Center, graduate fellowships at Brandeis University, Revson Plaza at Columbia University). He also contributed important sums of money to the Salk Institute and various charities.Although there had been some speculation about Mr. Revson's unwillingness to groom a successor, the guessing was brought to an end in 1974. Shortly before he underwent surgery, Mr. Revson named Michel G. Bergerac, former president of ITT Europe, Inc., as president of Revlon.Besides his brother, Martin, Mr. Revson is survived by two sons, John, Who is vice president of the company's. Etherea Fine Fragrance Division, and Charles Jr., who is director of marketing. fragrances of the Borghese Division an adopted daughter, Penelope Revson, and one grandchild. The sons are the children of his second marriage, to Joanna Katrinka de Knecht, who is now Mrs. Ben Johnson of Palm Beach, Fla. Mr. Revson's first marriage, to Ida Tompkins, also ended in divorce.A funeral service will he held tomorrow at 2 P.M. in Temple Emanu‐El, Fifth Avenue and 165th Street.
Continue reading the main story



















